[1
Date: Wed 17 Jan 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: WHO Disease Outbreaks Report, Wed 17 Jan 2001 [edited
<http://www.who.int/disease-outbreak-news/n2001/january/17january2001.html>

Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever in Uganda - WHO Update 39
--------------------------------------------------
As of Tue 16 Jan 2001, the Ugandan Ministry of Health has reported the
following:
Gulu district: One new confirmed case has been detected. The case is a
close contact of the patient who died on 4 Jan 2001. The cumulative total
number of cases is now 396 cases and 150 deaths.
Masindi district: No new cases have been reported since 19 Dec 2000. The
cumulative total number of cases remains 27 cases and 19 deaths.
WHO recommends no special restrictions on travel or trade to or from Uganda.
A team consisting of WHO, health authorities from the Ministry of Health of
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and Medecins sans Frontieres (MSF)
has investigated rumours of similar outbreaks in Bunia, DRC as
indicated. They have found no evidence of viral haemorrhagic fever. The
team reviewed procedures for dealing with suspected cases and identified
and trained local sampling and investigation teams.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The first part of this report appears to duplicate WHO Update 38 (posted
as Ebola hemorrhagic fever - Uganda (04)), which also recorded the death
toll in Gulu to be 150 on 9 Jan 2001, following the death of one additional
patient.
Now there would appear to be no substance to the reports of suspected cases
of Ebola haemorrhagic fever in the Democratic Republic of Congo, but it is
not clear from the WHO statement whether laboratory tests have been
undertaken. - Mod.CP
